description: Borrowed from Late Latin manifestātiō, in the political sense via French manifestation. By surface analysis, manifest +‎ -ation.

entries.meaning: The act or process of becoming manifest.
examples: The last known manifestation of the ghost was over ten years ago.

entries.meaning: The embodiment of an intangible, or variable thing.
examples: This particular manifestation resembled a young girl crying.

entries.meaning: (medicine) The symptoms or observable conditions which are seen as a result of some disease.
A pattern or logo on a sheet of glass, as decoration and/or to prevent people from accidentally walking into it.
